<tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" numbered="false" root="false"><frontmatter><anchor>8897</anchor> <rss>jms-00IJ.xml</rss> <taxon>Example</taxon> <addr>jms-00IJ</addr><route>jms-00IJ.xml</route>  <date><year>2024</year> <month>1</month> <day>17</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local" jonmsterling="addr">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>The integer square root <link href="jms-00I7.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00I7" title="Relation">relation</link></title>   </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>The square root operation corresponds to a relation <tex>R_2 \colon   \mathbb {N} \mathbin { \nrightarrow } \mathbb {Z}</tex> such that <tex>m \mathrel {R_2} n</tex> if and only if <tex>m = n^2</tex>.</p></mainmatter> <backmatter><contributions/> <context><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" numbered="false" root="false"><frontmatter><anchor>8898</anchor> <rss>jms-00IF.xml</rss>  <addr>jms-00IF</addr><route>jms-00IF.xml</route>  <date><year>2024</year> <month>1</month> <day>17</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local" jonmsterling="addr">Jon Sterling</link></author> <contributor><link href="marcelofiore.xml" type="local" marcelofiore="addr">Marcelo Fiore</link></contributor></authors> <title>Formal examples of <link href="jms-00I7.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00I7" title="Relation">relations</link></title>   </frontmatter> <mainmatter><tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" toc="true" numbered="true" root="false"><frontmatter><anchor>8899</anchor> <rss>jms-00IG.xml</rss> <taxon>Example</taxon> <addr>jms-00IG</addr><route>jms-00IG.xml</route>  <date><year>2024</year> <month>1</month> <day>17</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local" jonmsterling="addr">Jon Sterling</link></author> <contributor><link href="marcelofiore.xml" type="local" marcelofiore="addr">Marcelo Fiore</link></contributor></authors> <title>The empty <link href="jms-00I7.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00I7" title="Relation">relation</link></title>   </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>For any two sets <tex>A</tex> and <tex>B</tex>, we may form the <em><strong>empty <link href="jms-00I7.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00I7" title="Relation">relation</link></strong></em> <tex>\varnothing \colon  A \mathbin { \nrightarrow }  B</tex> that relates <em>no</em> elements. In other words, <tex>\varnothing</tex> is the empty subset of <tex>A \times  B</tex>.</p></mainmatter> </tree><tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" toc="true" numbered="true" root="false"><frontmatter><anchor>8900</anchor> <rss>jms-00IH.xml</rss> <taxon>Example</taxon> <addr>jms-00IH</addr><route>jms-00IH.xml</route>  <date><year>2024</year> <month>1</month> <day>17</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local" jonmsterling="addr">Jon Sterling</link></author> <contributor><link href="marcelofiore.xml" type="local" marcelofiore="addr">Marcelo Fiore</link></contributor></authors> <title>The full relation</title>   </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>For any two sets <tex>A</tex> and <tex>B</tex>, we may form the <em><strong>full <link href="jms-00I7.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00I7" title="Relation">relation</link></strong></em> <tex>{ \mathopen {} \left ( A \times  B \right ) \mathclose {}} \colon  A \mathbin { \nrightarrow }  B</tex>, also called the <em><strong>total <link href="jms-00I7.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00I7" title="Relation">relation</link></strong></em>, so that <tex>a \mathrel { { \mathopen {} \left ( A \times  B \right ) \mathclose {}} }b</tex> for all <tex>a \in  A</tex> and <tex>b \in  B</tex>. In other words, <tex>{ \mathopen {} \left ( A \times  B \right ) \mathclose {}}</tex> is the <em>total</em> subset of <tex>A \times  B</tex>. </p></mainmatter> </tree><tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" toc="true" numbered="true" root="false"><frontmatter><anchor>8901</anchor> <rss>jms-00II.xml</rss> <taxon>Example</taxon> <addr>jms-00II</addr><route>jms-00II.xml</route>  <date><year>2024</year> <month>1</month> <day>17</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local" jonmsterling="addr">Jon Sterling</link></author> <contributor><link href="marcelofiore.xml" type="local" marcelofiore="addr">Marcelo Fiore</link></contributor></authors> <title>The identity <link href="jms-00I7.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00I7" title="Relation">relation</link></title>   </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>For any set <tex>A</tex>, we can form the <em><strong>identity <link href="jms-00I7.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00I7" title="Relation">relation</link></strong></em> <tex>\mathsf {id}_{ A } \colon  A \mathbin { \nrightarrow }  A</tex>, also called the <em><strong>equality <link href="jms-00I7.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00I7" title="Relation">relation</link></strong></em>, which relates each element of <tex>A</tex> to itself. In other words, we have <tex>a \mathrel { \mathsf {id}_{ A } } a'</tex> if and only if <tex>a=a'</tex>.</p></mainmatter> </tree><p>We have already seen the <link href="jms-00I9.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00I9" title="Relations in program specification">square root relation from positive reals to reals</link>, which corresponds to a <em>total</em> but <em>many-valued</em> function. We can define an analogous relationship in <ref addr="jms-00IJ" href="jms-00IJ.xml" taxon="Example"/> below from positive integers (naturals) to integers, which will correspond to a <em>partial</em> and many-valued function.</p><tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" toc="true" numbered="true" root="false"><frontmatter><anchor>8902</anchor> <rss>jms-00IJ.xml</rss> <taxon>Example</taxon> <addr>jms-00IJ</addr><route>jms-00IJ.xml</route>  <date><year>2024</year> <month>1</month> <day>17</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local" jonmsterling="addr">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>The integer square root <link href="jms-00I7.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00I7" title="Relation">relation</link></title>   </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>The square root operation corresponds to a relation <tex>R_2 \colon   \mathbb {N} \mathbin { \nrightarrow } \mathbb {Z}</tex> such that <tex>m \mathrel {R_2} n</tex> if and only if <tex>m = n^2</tex>.</p></mainmatter> </tree></mainmatter> </tree></context> <related><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" numbered="false" root="false"><frontmatter><anchor>8903</anchor> <rss>jms-00I7.xml</rss> <taxon>Definition</taxon> <addr>jms-00I7</addr><route>jms-00I7.xml</route>  <date><year>2024</year> <month>1</month> <day>17</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local" jonmsterling="addr">Jon Sterling</link></author> <contributor><link href="marcelofiore.xml" type="local" marcelofiore="addr">Marcelo Fiore</link></contributor></authors> <title>Relation</title>   </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>A <em><strong>(binary) relation</strong></em> <tex>R</tex> from a set <tex>A</tex> to a set <tex>B</tex>, written <tex>R \colon  A \mathbin { \nrightarrow }  B</tex> or <tex>R \in   \mathrm {Rel} { \mathopen {} \left ( A,B \right ) \mathclose {}}</tex> is defined to be a subset <tex>R \subseteq  A \times  B</tex>. We shall typically write <tex>a \mathrel {R}b</tex> for <tex>{ \mathopen {} \left ( a,b \right ) \mathclose {}} \in  R</tex>. More generally, a <em><strong>relation between multiple sets</strong></em> <tex>{ \mathopen {} \left ( A_i \right ) \mathclose {}} _{i \in  I}</tex> is defined to be a subset of the cartesian product <tex>\prod _{i \in  I} A_i</tex>.</p></mainmatter> </tree></related> <backlinks><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" numbered="false" root="false"><frontmatter><anchor>8904</anchor> <rss>jms-00IF.xml</rss>  <addr>jms-00IF</addr><route>jms-00IF.xml</route>  <date><year>2024</year> <month>1</month> <day>17</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local" jonmsterling="addr">Jon Sterling</link></author> <contributor><link href="marcelofiore.xml" type="local" marcelofiore="addr">Marcelo Fiore</link></contributor></authors> <title>Formal examples of <link href="jms-00I7.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00I7" title="Relation">relations</link></title>   </frontmatter> <mainmatter><tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" toc="true" numbered="true" root="false"><frontmatter><anchor>8905</anchor> <rss>jms-00IG.xml</rss> <taxon>Example</taxon> <addr>jms-00IG</addr><route>jms-00IG.xml</route>  <date><year>2024</year> <month>1</month> <day>17</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local" jonmsterling="addr">Jon Sterling</link></author> <contributor><link href="marcelofiore.xml" type="local" marcelofiore="addr">Marcelo Fiore</link></contributor></authors> <title>The empty <link href="jms-00I7.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00I7" title="Relation">relation</link></title>   </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>For any two sets <tex>A</tex> and <tex>B</tex>, we may form the <em><strong>empty <link href="jms-00I7.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00I7" title="Relation">relation</link></strong></em> <tex>\varnothing \colon  A \mathbin { \nrightarrow }  B</tex> that relates <em>no</em> elements. In other words, <tex>\varnothing</tex> is the empty subset of <tex>A \times  B</tex>.</p></mainmatter> </tree><tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" toc="true" numbered="true" root="false"><frontmatter><anchor>8906</anchor> <rss>jms-00IH.xml</rss> <taxon>Example</taxon> <addr>jms-00IH</addr><route>jms-00IH.xml</route>  <date><year>2024</year> <month>1</month> <day>17</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local" jonmsterling="addr">Jon Sterling</link></author> <contributor><link href="marcelofiore.xml" type="local" marcelofiore="addr">Marcelo Fiore</link></contributor></authors> <title>The full relation</title>   </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>For any two sets <tex>A</tex> and <tex>B</tex>, we may form the <em><strong>full <link href="jms-00I7.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00I7" title="Relation">relation</link></strong></em> <tex>{ \mathopen {} \left ( A \times  B \right ) \mathclose {}} \colon  A \mathbin { \nrightarrow }  B</tex>, also called the <em><strong>total <link href="jms-00I7.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00I7" title="Relation">relation</link></strong></em>, so that <tex>a \mathrel { { \mathopen {} \left ( A \times  B \right ) \mathclose {}} }b</tex> for all <tex>a \in  A</tex> and <tex>b \in  B</tex>. In other words, <tex>{ \mathopen {} \left ( A \times  B \right ) \mathclose {}}</tex> is the <em>total</em> subset of <tex>A \times  B</tex>. </p></mainmatter> </tree><tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" toc="true" numbered="true" root="false"><frontmatter><anchor>8907</anchor> <rss>jms-00II.xml</rss> <taxon>Example</taxon> <addr>jms-00II</addr><route>jms-00II.xml</route>  <date><year>2024</year> <month>1</month> <day>17</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local" jonmsterling="addr">Jon Sterling</link></author> <contributor><link href="marcelofiore.xml" type="local" marcelofiore="addr">Marcelo Fiore</link></contributor></authors> <title>The identity <link href="jms-00I7.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00I7" title="Relation">relation</link></title>   </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>For any set <tex>A</tex>, we can form the <em><strong>identity <link href="jms-00I7.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00I7" title="Relation">relation</link></strong></em> <tex>\mathsf {id}_{ A } \colon  A \mathbin { \nrightarrow }  A</tex>, also called the <em><strong>equality <link href="jms-00I7.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00I7" title="Relation">relation</link></strong></em>, which relates each element of <tex>A</tex> to itself. In other words, we have <tex>a \mathrel { \mathsf {id}_{ A } } a'</tex> if and only if <tex>a=a'</tex>.</p></mainmatter> </tree><p>We have already seen the <link href="jms-00I9.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00I9" title="Relations in program specification">square root relation from positive reals to reals</link>, which corresponds to a <em>total</em> but <em>many-valued</em> function. We can define an analogous relationship in <ref addr="jms-00IJ" href="jms-00IJ.xml" taxon="Example"/> below from positive integers (naturals) to integers, which will correspond to a <em>partial</em> and many-valued function.</p><tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" toc="true" numbered="true" root="false"><frontmatter><anchor>8908</anchor> <rss>jms-00IJ.xml</rss> <taxon>Example</taxon> <addr>jms-00IJ</addr><route>jms-00IJ.xml</route>  <date><year>2024</year> <month>1</month> <day>17</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local" jonmsterling="addr">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>The integer square root <link href="jms-00I7.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00I7" title="Relation">relation</link></title>   </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>The square root operation corresponds to a relation <tex>R_2 \colon   \mathbb {N} \mathbin { \nrightarrow } \mathbb {Z}</tex> such that <tex>m \mathrel {R_2} n</tex> if and only if <tex>m = n^2</tex>.</p></mainmatter> </tree></mainmatter> </tree></backlinks> <references/></backmatter></tree>